# 5 Things I Learned After Completing PortSwigger Web Security Labs
### Lessons from a Beginner's Bug Bounty Journey

**By Rushi Venkatadri**

---

## Introduction

When I first started learning web security, I believed finding vulnerabilities was all about using powerful tools and memorizing payloads.

After spending time solving PortSwigger Web Security Academy labs, I realized I was completely wrong.

The biggest improvement wasn't learning more payloads—it was learning **how to think**.

Each lab challenged me to slow down, observe carefully, and understand how web applications actually work.

These are the five lessons that changed the way I approach bug bounty hunting.

---

# 1. Every Parameter Deserves Attention

One of the first habits I developed was to stop assuming that parameters were harmless.

Whether it was:

- URL parameters
- POST body values
- Cookies
- Headers
- JSON requests

every single parameter became something worth investigating.

A single modified value can completely change how an application behaves.

Many vulnerabilities begin with a simple question:

> "What happens if I change this?"

That curiosity became one of the most valuable skills I gained.

---

# 2. Burp Suite Is More Than Just a Proxy

When I first opened Burp Suite, I mainly used it to intercept requests.

Over time, I discovered how useful different tools inside Burp really are.

Some of the features I now rely on include:

- Proxy History
- Repeater
- Comparer
- HTTP Message Analysis

Repeater, in particular, changed how I test applications.

Instead of refreshing the browser repeatedly, I could modify requests quickly and observe exactly how the server responded.

Learning Burp wasn't about clicking buttons.

It was about understanding HTTP.

---

# 3. Read the Responses, Not Just the Status Code

One mistake I used to make was focusing only on HTTP status codes such as:

- 200 OK
- 403 Forbidden
- 404 Not Found

But the response body often tells a much bigger story.

Sometimes applications reveal:

- Hidden functionality
- Internal messages
- Debugging information
- User data
- Implementation details

The more carefully I read server responses, the more I realized that important clues are often hiding in plain sight.

---

# 4. Enumeration Wins More Than Complex Payloads

Before starting bug bounty, I thought success depended on clever payloads.

PortSwigger taught me something different.

Simple enumeration often reveals more than complicated attacks.

Examples include:

- Changing IDs
- Testing different user roles
- Exploring hidden endpoints
- Checking API behavior
- Modifying parameters
- Observing access control decisions

Most of my progress came from asking simple questions repeatedly rather than trying advanced exploits immediately.

---

# 5. The Biggest Skill Is Developing an Attacker's Mindset

This was probably the most important lesson.

Web security isn't about memorizing hundreds of vulnerabilities.

It's about asking questions that developers may never have considered.

Questions like:

- What if this value changes?
- What if I remove this parameter?
- What if another user accesses this object?
- What happens if authentication fails?
- Does the server actually verify this?

That mindset transformed how I look at web applications.

Instead of seeing pages, I now see requests, responses, trust boundaries, and opportunities to test assumptions.

---

# My Biggest Takeaway

PortSwigger didn't just teach me vulnerabilities.

It taught me how to investigate.

That difference is huge.

Learning payloads is useful.

Learning how to think is what makes someone grow as a security researcher.

---

# What's Next?

I'm continuing my journey by exploring:

- Hacker101 CTF
- Bug bounty methodology
- Web application security testing
- Reconnaissance techniques
- Practical bug hunting

I plan to document everything I learn along the way so that other beginners can learn with me.

---

# Final Thoughts

If you're just starting your cybersecurity journey, don't worry about completing hundreds of labs as quickly as possible.

Instead, focus on understanding **why** each vulnerability exists.

Take notes.

Experiment.

Repeat the lab.

Modify requests.

Think like an attacker.

That mindset will stay with you far longer than any single payload or technique.

Cybersecurity is a journey of continuous learning, and every lab solved is another step toward becoming a better security researcher.

